      p In Timanfaya National Park you become speechless in front of the arid landscape. Here the clock stops and the silence reigns, lair of the devil seems to be build into the rivers of lava. Here is what french author, Michel Houellebecq wrote about these bizarre lunar landscapes: "In front of us a huge fissure, several metres wide, snaked as far as the horizon, cutting through the grey surface of the earth's crust. The silence was absolute. This, I thought, is what the world will look like when it dies." This is what is written in books, but who wants to live between the covers of a book? So go there, experience yourself and do not forget to stop to salute the camels and eat an icecream. 

