      p After kilometers of arid landscape you do not expect to see vineyards. No, I am not hallucinating. In Lanzarote, there are vineyards, I swear. Just bear with me.

      p After we left Timanfaya National Park we drove around the centre of the island and in front of us it appeared a truly unique landscape. We stopped and started wondering of the sight of it: are they really growing the vines in this manor, in these black pits surrounded by stone walls? It seems that they do, and they have award winning wines grown this way. Each vine is individually grown in a sunken pit and about four to five meters wide and as the island can be windy they add a dry semi-circular rock wall. The vines are planted directly in the soil which is covered and protected by the small black lava stone. It creates an extraordinary view.

      p PS. Do not expect to pop down to your local shop to pick up a bottle of wine to try. You can find it only in Lanzarote or the neighbouring islands in the Canaries.

      p PS. In case you do find it somewhere else, please do tell us. We loved it!

